    <annotation>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Modus sit in scholijs, aphorismis, discursibus, commentationibus vllo modo. Qui Liuium ipsum intimè animaduertit, pla[e]runq[ue] 
                        habet abundè politicarum, militarium, Ethicarumq[ue] in omni genere animaduersionum.
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Livy"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Let there be a limit to annotations, aphorisms, treatises and commentaries, in some way. He who pays really close attention to Livy himself, 
                generally has an abundance of political, military, and ethical comments of all kinds. 
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Tam ditissima[e], quàm strenuissima[e], callidissima[e]q[ue] orbis nationi, non difficile fuit, Regibus imperare, mundoq[ue] dominari. 
                        Quot Reges in vna vrbe populari? pro se quisq[ue]. 
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                For a nation that was the richest, most active as well as the shrewdest in the world it was not difficult to command kings and dominate the 
                world. How many kings are there in one popularist city? Each one [strives] for himself.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Scitè Lucianus appellat Vlyssem, et Nestorem, parasitos Agamemnonis, iam tum imperantis. Abiecti est animi, non regij, aut generosi, 
                        viliter adularj. Reges Laconici, non reges, sed duces; non dico regaliùs, aut nobiliù, sed viriliùs sapuerunt. 
                        Agesilaum Xenophontis, et Plutarchi cogito, illoq[ue] multò minores. 
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Lucian"/> 
                <person name="Odysseus"/>
                <person name="Nestor of Gerenia"/> 
                <person name="Agamemnon"/>
                <person name="Xenophon"/>
                <person name="Plutarch"/>
                <person name="Agesilaus II"/> 
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Lucian expertly calls Odysseus and Nestor parasites of Agamemnon, who was in charge then already. Cheaply flattering is a sign of a base, 
                rather than a royal or noble, mind. Spartan kings were not kings, but leaders, who showed good sense – not to say in a more royal or noble way,
                but more manly. I am thinking of Xenophon’s and Plutarch’s Agesilaus, and of much lesser ones than him. 
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="Polybius" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        In Polybio no[n] minore[m], quàm in Liuio iacturam fecimus; ex quadraginta eius historiaru[m] libris, quinq[ue] tantùm residuis.  
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Polybius"/>
                <person name="Livy"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Of Polybius we lost no less than of Livy: only five of the forty books of his histories remain. 
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Tales reguli, sua[e], quàm publica[e] persona[e] cautiores, iuri maiestatis plurimùm detrahunt; et sibi, suisq[ue] 
                        posteris, non tam (
                        humili, quàm vili obsequio indignissimè pra[e]iudicant. Regium est, dicere, facereq[ue] regificè:
                        quicquid vsurpatur externi imperij. Sed Romanis, rerum dominis, mundiq[ue] occupatoribus, illo a[e]uo obsecundandum fuit. 
                    </marginalia_text>
                <emphasis method="pen" text="Romanis" type="straight"/>
                <emphasis method="pen" text="mundiq[ue]" type="straight"/>
                <emphasis method="pen" text="a[e]uo obsecundandum" type="straight"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                More concerned for themselves, rather than their public role, such petty kings detract most from the authority of majesty, and with their 
                cheap, rather than humble subservience create in advance an utterly shameful view of both themselves and their descendants. The royal thing to
                do is to speak and act as a king, whatever outward power is exercised. But in that period one had to comply with the Romans, the rulers of 
                affairs, the occupiers of the world.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Sir Thomas Smyth, the Queenes principal secretarie; in his trauails in Fraunce, Italie, Spaine, and Germanie; but especially in his 
                        ambassages in Scotland, Fraunce, and Netherlande; found no sutch use of anie autours, as I heard himself say, as of Liuie, Plutarch, 
                        &amp; Justinian. He mutch commended Sallust, Suetonius, Tacitus, &amp; sum other of the best: but his classical &amp; statarie historians 
                        were Liuie, Plutarch, Halicarnasseus; &amp; verie fewe other. Of the new, Cominaeus, Guicciardine, Jouius, Paulus Æmilius, Egnatius, 
                        &amp; but fewe other. Not the most, but the Best; was his rule. And I am for Geometrical, not Arithmetical proportion. An other of owre 
                        cunningest, &amp; shrewdest ambassadours in Fraunce, Sir Nicholas Throgmarton, was altogither for Cesar, &amp; Liuie; Liuie, &amp; Cesar. 
                        Not a more resolute man in Ingland: &amp; few deeper heds: as Mie Lord Burgley will still saye. 
                    </marginalia_text>
